To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the standard library. The `exit()` function takes an integer argument that represents the status code of the program. This status code is often used by the operating system to determine whether the program ran successfully or encountered an error.

Here's how you can use the `exit()` function in your C program:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program logic goes here

    // Terminate the program with a success status code (0)
    exit(0);
}
```

In this example, the program will terminate when it reaches the `exit(0)` call, and the operating system will interpret this as a successful termination.

If you want to terminate the program with an error status code, you can pass a non-zero value to the `exit()` function. For instance:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // Your program logic goes here

    // Terminate the program with an error status code (-1)
    exit(-1);
}
```

In this case, the program will terminate with an error status code, which might be useful for debugging purposes or if you want to handle errors differently at a higher level in your application.
